  <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">After you appeal</h2>

  <h3>If your appeal is successful</h3>
  <p>If your appeal is successful, you can go ahead with the planned work.</p>

  <h3>If your appeal is unsuccessful</h3>
  <p>If your appeal is unsuccessful, you can talk to your local planning department about making changes to your application before resubmitting.</p>

  <h3>If you disagree with the appeal decision</h3>
  <p>If you think the Planning Inspectorate made a legal mistake, you can challenge the decision in the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/courts-tribunals/administrative-court" target="_blank">High Court</a>.
  <p><a href="https://solicitors.lawsociety.org.uk/" target="_blank">Get advice from a lawyer</a> if you’re unsure about this.

  <h3>If you want to complain</h3>
  <p>You can <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/planning-inspectorate/about/complaints-procedure" target="_blank">complain</a> about how the Planning Inspectorate handled your appeal. There’s no time limit for complaints.</p>
